Result: Command message_agent returned: Sure, here are the steps to generate an SSH key and add it to your GitHub account:

1. Open your terminal or command prompt.
2. Type `ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your_email@example.com"` and press Enter. This will generate a new SSH key pair.
3. You will be prompted to enter a file name to save the key. Press Enter to accept the default file name and location.
4. You will be prompted to enter a passphrase. You can either enter a passphrase or leave it blank for no passphrase. Press Enter to continue.
5. Your SSH key pair has been generated. To view the public key, type `cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub` and press Enter.
6. Copy the entire contents of the public key to your clipboard.
7. Log in to your GitHub account and go to your account settings.
8. Click on "SSH and GPG keys" in the left sidebar.
9. Click on "New SSH key" or "Add SSH key".
10. Enter a title for the key (e.g. "My SSH key").
11. Paste the public key into the "Key" field.
12. Click "Add SSH key" to save the key to your GitHub account.

Now you can clone the repository using the SSH URL and you will not be prompted for your username and password.
